1
00:00:06,200 --> 00:00:07,368
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

2
00:00:07,452 --> 00:00:09,370
Hello?

3
00:00:09,454 --> 00:00:11,997
[INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER RADIO]

4
00:00:12,081 --> 00:00:13,624
Hello?

5
00:00:13,708 --> 00:00:16,126
Oh, boy.

6
00:00:16,210 --> 00:00:18,379
-You remember me?
-Oh, yeah.

7
00:00:18,463 --> 00:00:20,506
-Long time no see.
-Oh, yes.

8
00:00:20,590 --> 00:00:23,885
Well, I've been very busy. Traveling.

9
00:00:23,969 --> 00:00:27,514
-You want a slice?
-Oh, no, thank you.

10
00:00:27,598 --> 00:00:28,890
I was just in the neighborhood,

11
00:00:28,974 --> 00:00:31,101
and I thought I would
drop in and say hello.

12
00:00:31,185 --> 00:00:33,187
-To me.
-Yes.

13
00:00:37,733 --> 00:00:40,902
-Hello.
-Hello.

14
00:00:40,986 --> 00:00:43,154
Anything else?

15
00:00:43,238 --> 00:00:45,156
No.

16
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:47,158
Oh, well, as long as I'm here,

17
00:00:47,242 --> 00:00:50,161
Miriam… my daughter, remember?

18
00:00:50,245 --> 00:00:54,207
Well, her husband left her,
and she's been living with us,

19
00:00:54,291 --> 00:00:56,334
and recently I found out that she's…

20
00:00:56,418 --> 00:00:58,336
Aren't you gonna make some tea?

21
00:00:58,420 --> 00:01:00,255
-I don't like tea.
-[CHUCKLES] The tea isn't for you.

22
00:01:00,339 --> 00:01:01,756
It's for me. I drink it,

23
00:01:01,840 --> 00:01:03,925
-and you read the leaves.
-Don't need it.

24
00:01:04,009 --> 00:01:07,387
Oh, you use the ball, right. Or cards?

25
00:01:07,471 --> 00:01:09,764
Oh, no, I remember. You like fire.

26
00:01:09,848 --> 00:01:12,310
Just sit there.

27
00:01:12,394 --> 00:01:14,396
Let me look at you.

28
00:01:22,988 --> 00:01:25,323
Okay. What do you want to know?

29
00:01:25,407 --> 00:01:26,991
Um, well, my d… daughter…

30
00:01:27,075 --> 00:01:28,534
-Miriam.
-Why, yes.

31
00:01:28,618 --> 00:01:30,494
You just told me her name.
Don't get too impressed.

32
00:01:30,578 --> 00:01:35,124
Yes, uh, well, she's,
um, pursuing a career in

33
00:01:35,208 --> 00:01:39,211
comedy, which is bad enough in itself,

34
00:01:39,295 --> 00:01:41,964
but there's a very viable
man in the picture now,

35
00:01:42,048 --> 00:01:44,967
and I am so worried that this

36
00:01:45,051 --> 00:01:48,429
career will be the
downfall of this relationship.

37
00:01:48,513 --> 00:01:50,014
Tell me, what do you see?

38
00:01:50,098 --> 00:01:52,100
Hmm.

39
00:01:54,477 --> 00:01:58,815
I see a perky brunette
with a signature hairstyle.

40
00:01:58,899 --> 00:02:00,984
Oh, that's her. That's Miriam.

41
00:02:01,068 --> 00:02:02,653
She's standing in front of a big crowd.

42
00:02:02,737 --> 00:02:04,237
A wedding? That's a wedding.

43
00:02:04,321 --> 00:02:06,531
She's the object of deep adoration.

44
00:02:06,615 --> 00:02:08,700
That's Benjamin. He'll adore her.

45
00:02:08,784 --> 00:02:10,786
H… He'll be weirdly subtle about it

46
00:02:10,870 --> 00:02:12,537
and do it in a slightly robotic way, but…

47
00:02:12,621 --> 00:02:14,623
I see her talking.

48
00:02:14,707 --> 00:02:17,876
Speaking very quickly into a microphone.

49
00:02:17,960 --> 00:02:19,711
That's her speech.
She gave a speech at her first wedding,

50
00:02:19,795 --> 00:02:21,672
and she's doing it again. Oh, I'm so…

51
00:02:21,756 --> 00:02:23,340
Does she mention shrimp?

52
00:02:23,424 --> 00:02:24,925
-What?
-Never mind. Who cares?

53
00:02:25,009 --> 00:02:26,927
She's getting married. Oh, I'm so glad

54
00:02:27,011 --> 00:02:29,846
I just happened to be strolling
by here with no intention

55
00:02:29,930 --> 00:02:32,180
of coming in at all, and then I did.
Oh, here.

56
00:02:32,892 --> 00:02:34,977
Thank you.

57
00:02:35,061 --> 00:02:38,271
Thank you so much.
I'll see you next week.

58
00:02:38,355 --> 00:02:41,608
There's gonna be a wedding.

59
00:02:41,692 --> 00:02:43,653
[CHUCKLES]

60
00:02:44,696 --> 00:02:46,406
I don't know why you'd wear

61
00:02:46,490 --> 00:02:50,326
a black cocktail dress to a wedding, but

62
00:02:50,410 --> 00:02:52,412
whatever.

63
00:02:55,248 --> 00:02:58,167
[ANNOUNCER SHOUTING OVER RADIO]

64
00:02:58,251 --> 00:03:00,503
-What time is it?
-Early. 9:00, 10:00.

65
00:03:00,587 --> 00:03:03,631
-12:30. I should go.
-Really? You bored?

66
00:03:03,715 --> 00:03:05,550
I'm supposed to be in
my dorm room by midnight.

67
00:03:05,634 --> 00:03:07,552
This is the third time this
week I've missed curfew.

68
00:03:07,636 --> 00:03:09,262
Third time this week I'll
have to climb in my window

69
00:03:09,346 --> 00:03:11,347
-to avoid getting caught.
-I thought your curfew was 1:00.

70
00:03:11,431 --> 00:03:13,141
-You did not.
-Yeah.

71
00:03:13,225 --> 00:03:15,268
I just like watching you
climb in that window.

72
00:03:15,352 --> 00:03:17,895
Hey, we saw them tonight.
We saw you tonight.

73
00:03:17,979 --> 00:03:19,188
-Oh, yeah?
-Mm-hmm.

74
00:03:19,272 --> 00:03:20,356
-Good or bad?
-Great.

75
00:03:20,440 --> 00:03:21,733
Especially the last number.

76
00:03:21,817 --> 00:03:23,526
Told you we needed that last number.

77
00:03:23,610 --> 00:03:26,154
-You're impossible.
-Impossible and right.

78
00:03:26,238 --> 00:03:27,905
-We should go.
-You know, I'm tired

79
00:03:27,989 --> 00:03:29,490
of having to take you home at night.

80
00:03:29,574 --> 00:03:31,493
-I can just grab a cab, then.
-Not what I meant.

81
00:03:31,577 --> 00:03:34,329
-Horse and buggy? Magic carpet?
-Don't go back to your dorm.

82
00:03:34,413 --> 00:03:36,540
-Where am I supposed to go?
-My dorm.

83
00:03:36,624 --> 00:03:39,209
Oh, now, Mr. Maisel, you know good girls

84
00:03:39,293 --> 00:03:41,170
don't stay out all night
with their gentlemen callers.

85
00:03:41,254 --> 00:03:43,422
I mean, what would the neighbors think?

86
00:03:43,506 --> 00:03:45,132
That you're a dime-store floozy?

87
00:03:45,216 --> 00:03:47,051
Dime-store? In these shoes?

88
00:03:47,135 --> 00:03:50,387
Well, if you won't let
me sully your reputation,

89
00:03:50,471 --> 00:03:53,265
then I guess I'll just have to
make an honest woman out of you.

90
00:03:53,349 --> 00:03:55,601
<i>♪ We go along harmonizing a song ♪</i>

91
00:03:55,685 --> 00:03:57,728
-What's this?
-A Cadillac.

92
00:03:57,812 --> 00:03:59,271
<i>♪ Or I'm reciting a poem ♪</i>

93
00:03:59,355 --> 00:04:02,107
Well, then, I'm definitely
gonna have to learn to drive.

94
00:04:02,191 --> 00:04:04,318
-You like it?
-I love it.

95
00:04:04,402 --> 00:04:06,278
I just didn't think this
would happen so fast.

96
00:04:06,362 --> 00:04:07,654
Oh, but you knew this would happen?

97
00:04:07,738 --> 00:04:09,364
Well, yeah. I mean, come on.

98
00:04:09,448 --> 00:04:11,492
Hey, what did my father
say when you asked him?

99
00:04:11,576 --> 00:04:13,160
Oh, shit. I was supposed to do that?

100
00:04:13,244 --> 00:04:15,454
-Joel.
-Forget him.

101
00:04:15,538 --> 00:04:18,374
What do you say? Yes? Great.

102
00:04:18,458 --> 00:04:20,543
I say I need to think about it.

103
00:04:20,627 --> 00:04:23,296
What? No. There's the ring. Let's go.

104
00:04:23,380 --> 00:04:26,174
-It's just so sudden.
-You knew this was gonna happen.

105
00:04:26,258 --> 00:04:27,467
I knew this was gonna happen.

106
00:04:27,551 --> 00:04:29,260
Well, then, you know your answer.

107
00:04:29,344 --> 00:04:32,180
-Uh…
-If you don't say yes right now,

108
00:04:32,264 --> 00:04:33,890
I'm gonna walk out in
the middle of the street

109
00:04:33,974 --> 00:04:35,391
and wait for a bus to run me over.

110
00:04:35,475 --> 00:04:36,976
Pay the bill first?

111
00:04:37,060 --> 00:04:39,437
Okay.

112
00:04:39,521 --> 00:04:42,065
-Here I go.
-[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

113
00:04:42,149 --> 00:04:43,775
<i>♪ Talking my baby ♪</i>

114
00:04:43,859 --> 00:04:45,777
<i>♪ Loving my baby ♪</i>

115
00:04:45,861 --> 00:04:47,612
<i>♪ I don't mean maybe… ♪</i>

116
00:04:47,696 --> 00:04:49,072
[HORNS HONKING]

117
00:04:49,156 --> 00:04:51,491
That man is crazy.

118
00:04:51,575 --> 00:04:54,410
Yeah, he certainly is.

119
00:04:54,494 --> 00:04:55,954
MAN: Get out of the road, asshole.

120
00:04:56,038 --> 00:04:57,330
-Come on!
-[TIRES SCREECHING]

121
00:04:57,414 --> 00:04:58,728
-Say yes.
-No.

122
00:04:58,812 --> 00:05:00,125
MAN: Move!

123
00:05:00,209 --> 00:05:02,502
-Move, you idiot!
-Not moving.

124
00:05:02,586 --> 00:05:05,840
I'm concerned our children
might come out clinically insane.

125
00:05:05,924 --> 00:05:08,509
Very good chance. Say yes.

126
00:05:08,593 --> 00:05:10,427
Maybe.

127
00:05:10,511 --> 00:05:11,554
MAN: Get the fuck out of the road, pal.

128
00:05:11,638 --> 00:05:12,847
MAN 2: Come on, I got to get home.

129
00:05:12,931 --> 00:05:14,515
<i>♪ Are in each other's arms ♪</i>

130
00:05:14,599 --> 00:05:17,852
Oh, no. Not fair.

131
00:05:17,936 --> 00:05:19,270
-Fuck fair!
-MAN: Come on.

132
00:05:19,354 --> 00:05:20,855
My favorite show.

133
00:05:20,939 --> 00:05:23,149
-He took me three times.
-[WOMEN CHUCKLE]

134
00:05:23,233 --> 00:05:24,984
I'm going for broke, Miriam Weissman.

135
00:05:25,068 --> 00:05:28,320
<i>♪ Shall we dance? ♪</i>

136
00:05:28,404 --> 00:05:30,239
You have to say yes first.

137
00:05:30,323 --> 00:05:31,532
<i>♪ On a bright cloud of music ♪</i>

138
00:05:31,616 --> 00:05:34,076
Fine. Yes.

139
00:05:34,160 --> 00:05:36,829
-Yes! [GIGGLES]
-[HONKING CONTINUES]

140
00:05:36,913 --> 00:05:39,206
You have to put the ring on.

141
00:05:39,290 --> 00:05:42,251
-Exhausting.
-JOEL: Put it on.

142
00:05:42,335 --> 00:05:44,128
MAN: Come on, move it, buddy.

143
00:05:44,212 --> 00:05:47,464
<i>♪ When the last little
star has left the sky ♪</i>

144
00:05:47,548 --> 00:05:49,676
<i>♪ Shall we still be together ♪</i>

145
00:05:49,760 --> 00:05:51,887
<i>♪ With our arms around each other ♪</i>

146
00:05:51,971 --> 00:05:55,265
<i>♪ And shall you be my new romance ♪</i>

147
00:05:55,349 --> 00:05:56,516
[CROWD CHEERS]

148
00:05:56,600 --> 00:05:58,643
<i>♪ On the clear understanding ♪</i>

149
00:05:58,727 --> 00:06:00,562
<i>♪ That this kind of thing can happen ♪</i>

150
00:06:00,646 --> 00:06:02,022
<i>♪ Shall we dance? ♪</i>

151
00:06:02,106 --> 00:06:05,109
Now, this next part's
gonna go very badly.

152
00:06:07,611 --> 00:06:09,613
[CROWD CHEERING]

153
00:06:13,325 --> 00:06:15,327
[APPLAUSE]

154
00:06:28,132 --> 00:06:30,134
[BENJAMIN SPEAKING SOFTLY NEARBY]

155
00:06:36,683 --> 00:06:39,018
BENJAMIN: Mark Greenwald
is the president of the bank

156
00:06:39,102 --> 00:06:41,646
and an old family friend in
case you want to give him a call.

157
00:06:41,730 --> 00:06:44,690
Right here, these are
last year's financials,

158
00:06:44,774 --> 00:06:46,234
tax returns, bank statements.

159
00:06:46,318 --> 00:06:47,944
As you can see, I can
clearly provide for her.

160
00:06:48,028 --> 00:06:49,820
Anything she needs,
anything the children need,

161
00:06:49,904 --> 00:06:51,530
they will be very comfortable.

162
00:06:51,614 --> 00:06:55,243
So you want to marry my daughter.

163
00:06:55,327 --> 00:06:57,536
With your permission, yes, I do.

164
00:06:57,620 --> 00:07:00,998
-And you've spent time with Miriam.
-I have.

165
00:07:01,082 --> 00:07:03,376
-So you understand Miriam.
-I do.

166
00:07:03,460 --> 00:07:05,503
Could you explain her to me?

167
00:07:05,587 --> 00:07:08,422
-That was a joke, Benjamin.
-Right, sorry.

168
00:07:08,506 --> 00:07:11,133
Humor is very important
in our house, Benjamin.

169
00:07:11,217 --> 00:07:13,302
-Of course.
-If you are going to marry Miriam,

170
00:07:13,386 --> 00:07:15,012
-you will have to learn that.
-I understand.

171
00:07:15,096 --> 00:07:16,681
Because to Miriam, almost
everything in the world

172
00:07:16,765 --> 00:07:19,850
is a joke.
I had to stop watching the news with her.

173
00:07:19,934 --> 00:07:21,602
Guggenheim, the name of the museum,

174
00:07:21,686 --> 00:07:24,061
caused 20 minutes of
uncontrolled giggling.

175
00:07:24,145 --> 00:07:24,648
[LAUGHS]

176
00:07:24,732 --> 00:07:27,859
Why? Who knows. That's just Miriam.

177
00:07:27,943 --> 00:07:29,111
I will learn to laugh, sir.

178
00:07:29,195 --> 00:07:31,113
You're going to need
a lot of closet space.

179
00:07:31,197 --> 00:07:33,657
-I have seen the hats.
-There will be a lot of activity.

180
00:07:33,741 --> 00:07:35,284
Things will shift quickly.

181
00:07:35,368 --> 00:07:38,328
Your reality, your vacation plans.

182
00:07:38,412 --> 00:07:40,289
And God knows what
those children will be like

183
00:07:40,373 --> 00:07:42,207
when they grow up.
I cannot vouch for them.

184
00:07:42,291 --> 00:07:44,293
I will not hold you responsible.

185
00:07:44,377 --> 00:07:46,503
It's awfully quick, your courtship.

186
00:07:46,587 --> 00:07:49,089
Anything I should know that
will certainly kill her mother?

187
00:07:49,173 --> 00:07:51,591
No. I've just waited a long
time to find the right person,

188
00:07:51,675 --> 00:07:53,176
and now I have. That's all.

189
00:07:53,260 --> 00:07:57,264
ABE: Well, if this is
truly your intention,

190
00:07:57,348 --> 00:07:59,266
in addition to the bank records,

191
00:07:59,350 --> 00:08:03,186
I will need 25 character references.

192
00:08:03,270 --> 00:08:05,063
Are you going to write this down?

193
00:08:05,147 --> 00:08:06,523
There's a list. I'll need to know

194
00:08:06,607 --> 00:08:08,608
the names and birth dates of your family,

195
00:08:08,692 --> 00:08:11,571
how religious you are,
what your hobbies are,

196
00:08:11,655 --> 00:08:14,866
what percentage of time
you spend on such hobbies,

197
00:08:14,950 --> 00:08:16,868
are you a dog or a cat man

198
00:08:16,952 --> 00:08:19,746
very important… your favorite authors.

199
00:08:19,830 --> 00:08:22,790
You see, Benjamin, after the Joel fiasco,

200
00:08:22,874 --> 00:08:24,208
I am taking this decision

201
00:08:24,292 --> 00:08:25,877
very, very seriously.

202
00:08:26,920 --> 00:08:29,589
You have somewhere else to be?

203
00:08:29,673 --> 00:08:32,175
No. Well, surgery.

204
00:08:32,259 --> 00:08:34,302
But never mind. Go on.

205
00:08:34,386 --> 00:08:36,387
I'll need to know all
political affiliations,

206
00:08:36,471 --> 00:08:37,638
favorite baseball team,

207
00:08:37,722 --> 00:08:39,140
favorite radio shows…

208
00:08:39,224 --> 00:08:41,309
Mr. Weissman, could
you excuse me a minute?

209
00:08:41,393 --> 00:08:43,144
I need to use the bathroom.

210
00:08:43,228 --> 00:08:46,606
Oh. That's something you do?

211
00:08:46,690 --> 00:08:48,649
Yes.

212
00:08:48,733 --> 00:08:50,735
All right. If you must.

213
00:08:55,365 --> 00:08:57,368
Oh.

214
00:08:59,370 --> 00:09:01,663
-What was that for?
-I just needed to make sure

215
00:09:01,747 --> 00:09:03,540
-you're worth all this.
-I am.

216
00:09:03,624 --> 00:09:05,584
God, this is much harder
than I thought it was gonna be.

217
00:09:05,668 --> 00:09:07,878
My father's a complicated man.
But once this is over,

218
00:09:07,962 --> 00:09:09,254
you guys are going to be very close.

219
00:09:09,338 --> 00:09:11,298
-It will never be over.
-It will be.

220
00:09:11,382 --> 00:09:13,133
Four patients have
already died this morning.

221
00:09:13,217 --> 00:09:15,677
-A small price to pay.
-I thought we were making progress

222
00:09:15,761 --> 00:09:17,304
when we stumbled
onto the Big Bang theory.

223
00:09:17,388 --> 00:09:19,348
How do you stumble
onto the Big Bang theory?

224
00:09:19,432 --> 00:09:21,350
And then he asked if I
snack in between meals.

225
00:09:21,434 --> 00:09:23,018
-You said no, right?
-I said it depends.

226
00:09:23,102 --> 00:09:25,270
-Oh, dear.
-It does. It's snacking.

227
00:09:25,354 --> 00:09:27,022
There's no plan.
That's what makes it snacking.

228
00:09:27,106 --> 00:09:29,608
Okay, relax. You're doing fine.
And get back in there.

229
00:09:29,692 --> 00:09:31,235
If he thinks you're taking
too long in the bathroom,

230
00:09:31,319 --> 00:09:32,569
there will be a very thorough physical

231
00:09:32,653 --> 00:09:34,655
-in your future.
-Bye.

232
00:09:36,365 --> 00:09:38,283
Is this how you look in the morning?

233
00:09:38,367 --> 00:09:39,868
Yes, it is.

234
00:09:39,952 --> 00:09:42,287
I'll never make it to work on time again.

235
00:09:42,371 --> 00:09:44,416
-I'm back.
-ABE: That was quick. Good for you.

236
00:09:44,500 --> 00:09:46,376
Get these downstairs to Accounting now

237
00:09:46,460 --> 00:09:48,169
-or no one gets paid.
-ALL: What?!

238
00:09:48,253 --> 00:09:50,422
Everyone's getting paid!
It's an expression.

239
00:09:50,506 --> 00:09:53,049
-Get back to work.
-Mr. Maisel, phone.

240
00:09:53,133 --> 00:09:54,676
The Dutch fabric shipment's gone missing.

241
00:09:54,760 --> 00:09:56,428
How does a truckload
of fabric go missing?

242
00:09:56,512 --> 00:09:58,430
-Joel, are we on for tonight?
-I have the kids tonight.

243
00:09:58,514 --> 00:10:00,390
-I love kids.
-Great. Go have some.

244
00:10:00,474 --> 00:10:03,017
-Never mind, they found it.
-Where?

245
00:10:03,101 --> 00:10:05,270
Times Square. The driver had an audition.

246
00:10:05,354 --> 00:10:07,522
Get the shipment, fire the driver.
In that order.

247
00:10:07,606 --> 00:10:09,190
Okay, see, when I gave you

248
00:10:09,274 --> 00:10:11,568
that giant amount of money to go away,

249
00:10:11,652 --> 00:10:14,404
-I expected you to go away.
-I don't have time right now, Pop.

250
00:10:14,488 --> 00:10:17,574
I fired you, and you responded
by bringing your children here.

251
00:10:17,658 --> 00:10:20,660
Is that hostile or adorable?
I just can't tell.

252
00:10:20,744 --> 00:10:23,246
I'll go. I'm going.
I just have to figure out where.

253
00:10:23,330 --> 00:10:24,747
In the meantime, Mrs. Moskowitz,

254
00:10:24,831 --> 00:10:26,124
when is the Joseph Miller meeting again?

255
00:10:26,208 --> 00:10:27,709
-4:45.
-4:45?

256
00:10:27,793 --> 00:10:29,336
That's what he said, 4:45.

257
00:10:29,420 --> 00:10:31,255
Hey, what are you drawing there, Ethan?

258
00:10:31,339 --> 00:10:33,424
Mommy's friend. Bathroom!

259
00:10:33,508 --> 00:10:36,552
Mr. Maisel, I am not
cleaning that bathroom again.

260
00:10:36,636 --> 00:10:38,304
I got it, Mrs. Moskowitz.

261
00:10:38,388 --> 00:10:40,973
He's like a sprung
garden hose, that child.

262
00:10:41,057 --> 00:10:43,058
-Mommy's got a friend.
-Fuck you.

263
00:10:43,142 --> 00:10:45,936
Aha, baby's first swear word.

264
00:10:46,020 --> 00:10:48,147
Definitely not her first.

265
00:10:50,191 --> 00:10:52,818
What is your life, anyhow?

266
00:10:52,902 --> 00:10:55,279
JOEL: Ethan!

267
00:10:55,363 --> 00:10:57,615
Remember, pal, you have
to look where you're aiming

268
00:10:57,699 --> 00:10:59,492
-when you use the urinal.
-Why?

269
00:10:59,576 --> 00:11:02,369
Because if you keep hitting
the floor and the counter

270
00:11:02,453 --> 00:11:05,206
and the ceiling, no girl's
ever gonna marry you,

271
00:11:05,290 --> 00:11:06,790
and Mrs. Moskowitz is
gonna leave your daddy,

272
00:11:06,874 --> 00:11:08,334
so we'll both be alone.

273
00:11:08,418 --> 00:11:11,504
Hey. So, Mommy has a new friend, huh?

274
00:11:11,588 --> 00:11:13,214
-Yeah.
-And you met him?

275
00:11:13,298 --> 00:11:14,798
-Yeah.
-Where?

276
00:11:14,882 --> 00:11:16,051
At the park.

277
00:11:18,095 --> 00:11:19,721
I thought you had to go to the bathroom.

278
00:11:19,805 --> 00:11:21,807
ETHAN: Not fun now!

279
00:11:23,851 --> 00:11:26,854
-This one?
-Second wedding.

280
00:11:30,441 --> 00:11:33,444
-This one?
-Second wedding.

281
00:11:35,988 --> 00:11:37,447
-This one.
-Miriam, please.

282
00:11:37,531 --> 00:11:39,783
You can't wear white.
It's a second wedding.

283
00:11:39,867 --> 00:11:42,786
-You can wear champagne.
-I don't want to wear champagne.

284
00:11:42,870 --> 00:11:45,121
It's not a color.
It's what happens when white gets sad.

285
00:11:45,205 --> 00:11:48,250
Well, I'm sorry.
Second weddings are subtle, dignified.

286
00:11:48,334 --> 00:11:50,710
No big halls or lavish dinners.

287
00:11:50,794 --> 00:11:52,796
Second weddings mean 40 guests

288
00:11:52,880 --> 00:11:54,756
and a luncheon at home
with scrambled eggs.

289
00:11:54,840 --> 00:11:56,383
Wow. What's the third wedding mean?

290
00:11:56,467 --> 00:11:57,842
Third wedding means I'm dead.

291
00:11:57,926 --> 00:11:59,886
-Can I wear white?
-Keep looking, please.

292
00:11:59,970 --> 00:12:01,680
There may not even
be a wedding at this rate.

293
00:12:01,764 --> 00:12:03,474
Papa still hasn't said yes.

294
00:12:03,558 --> 00:12:04,934
Plus, he said if he does say yes,

295
00:12:05,018 --> 00:12:06,978
-he's not gonna pay for it.
-Yes, he will.

296
00:12:07,062 --> 00:12:09,730
He'll pay for a second wedding
here at home with scrambled…

297
00:12:09,814 --> 00:12:11,857
Scrambled eggs and a champagne dress.

298
00:12:11,941 --> 00:12:13,609
Oh, now cheer up.
You can still give a toast.

299
00:12:13,693 --> 00:12:15,653
I know you have your
heart set on giving a toast.

300
00:12:15,737 --> 00:12:17,196
-How do you know that?
-Ladies.

301
00:12:17,280 --> 00:12:18,864
Papa. Hi!

302
00:12:18,948 --> 00:12:21,367
There's a sandwich for
you in the refrigerator, Abe.

303
00:12:21,451 --> 00:12:24,036
Papa? Hey, Papa?

304
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:25,871
Papa? Papa?

305
00:12:25,955 --> 00:12:27,915
Miriam, do you get paid by the "Papa"?

306
00:12:27,999 --> 00:12:30,084
-No.
-[SIGHS]

307
00:12:30,168 --> 00:12:33,170
-So, Papa…
-Pickles.

308
00:12:33,254 --> 00:12:35,298
I was just wondering if
you've thought any more

309
00:12:35,382 --> 00:12:36,841
about your talk with Benjamin?

310
00:12:36,925 --> 00:12:39,385
-No.
-No? Just no?

311
00:12:39,469 --> 00:12:41,596
No. Yes, no.

312
00:12:41,680 --> 00:12:44,265
Well, you know from experience,
the sooner you book a hall,

313
00:12:44,349 --> 00:12:45,725
the better deal you get.

314
00:12:45,809 --> 00:12:47,560
ROSE: No hall! Second wedding!

315
00:12:47,644 --> 00:12:49,521
I do not have an answer yet.

316
00:12:49,605 --> 00:12:52,190
Well, is there anything you
want to talk about with me?

317
00:12:52,274 --> 00:12:54,401
-No.
-Anything I can tell you?

318
00:12:54,485 --> 00:12:56,903
-No. Wait. Yes.
-Great. What?

319
00:12:56,987 --> 00:12:58,905
Do you ever call him Ben?

320
00:12:58,989 --> 00:13:00,907
-No.
-Benny?

321
00:13:00,991 --> 00:13:02,993
-No.
-Dr. Ben?

322
00:13:03,077 --> 00:13:04,953
-No.
-Okay.

323
00:13:05,037 --> 00:13:07,080
Thank you for that information.

324
00:13:07,164 --> 00:13:10,083
Papa? Papa…

325
00:13:10,167 --> 00:13:12,544
For a woman who wants to
make her fortune on the stage,

326
00:13:12,628 --> 00:13:14,421
you have an extremely limited vocabulary.

327
00:13:14,505 --> 00:13:16,006
Why won't you give your permission?

328
00:13:16,090 --> 00:13:17,841
I didn't say I wouldn't
give my permission.

329
00:13:17,925 --> 00:13:19,509
I just said I haven't decided yet.

330
00:13:19,593 --> 00:13:21,094
Well, what's taking you so long?

331
00:13:21,178 --> 00:13:23,055
I have to run his numbers again.

332
00:13:23,139 --> 00:13:24,681
I don't think his figures add up.

333
00:13:24,765 --> 00:13:26,350
It's not fair to make him wait.

334
00:13:26,434 --> 00:13:28,060
Well, if he doesn't like it,

335
00:13:28,144 --> 00:13:30,479
he can go ahead and marry
you without my permission.

336
00:13:30,563 --> 00:13:32,230
Joel did. That turned out great.

337
00:13:32,314 --> 00:13:34,775
Forget it.

338
00:13:34,859 --> 00:13:36,653
When I've decided, you'll know.

339
00:13:36,737 --> 00:13:38,696
-Fine.
-I'll send up a flare.

340
00:13:38,780 --> 00:13:40,740
Super.

341
00:13:40,824 --> 00:13:42,659
Miriam, wait.

342
00:13:42,743 --> 00:13:45,078
I need to ask you something.

343
00:13:48,123 --> 00:13:50,625
What did you say in Washington?

344
00:13:50,709 --> 00:13:52,752
What did I say about what?

345
00:13:52,836 --> 00:13:55,672
In your club date… what did you say about

346
00:13:55,756 --> 00:13:57,382
about me?

347
00:13:57,466 --> 00:13:59,384
Papa, I swear, that
night in the Catskills

348
00:13:59,468 --> 00:14:01,636
was a total and complete anomaly.

349
00:14:01,720 --> 00:14:03,971
-So you didn't talk about me at all?
-I did not.

350
00:14:04,055 --> 00:14:06,391
Cross my heart and swear
to God on the life of my kids.

351
00:14:06,475 --> 00:14:08,726
-Oh, wait.
-You did talk about me.

352
00:14:08,810 --> 00:14:10,520
-Just a little.
-What did you say?

353
00:14:10,604 --> 00:14:13,106
-It's very important that I know.
-I said,

354
00:14:13,190 --> 00:14:14,732
"Is Senator Kennedy
running for president?

355
00:14:14,816 --> 00:14:16,693
"It's up to Jackie.
You know she wears the pants

356
00:14:16,777 --> 00:14:18,528
-in that family."
-No, she doesn't.

357
00:14:18,612 --> 00:14:19,987
Well, I haven't gotten to
the part about the linen.

358
00:14:20,071 --> 00:14:21,406
-What linen?
-Her pants are linen.

359
00:14:21,490 --> 00:14:23,283
-Who cares what fabric they are?
-No.

360
00:14:23,367 --> 00:14:25,828
The whole point of the
bit is she wears linen pants,

361
00:14:25,912 --> 00:14:27,621
and they wrinkle while
you're ironing them.

362
00:14:27,705 --> 00:14:30,249
You know, you don't seem
to be getting any better at this.

363
00:14:30,333 --> 00:14:32,042
-Let me start again.
-Please don't.

364
00:14:32,126 --> 00:14:34,086
Just skip to the part about me.

365
00:14:34,170 --> 00:14:37,548
I said, I found you listening
to my four-year-old's record,

366
00:14:37,632 --> 00:14:39,842
a song about teaching yourself

367
00:14:39,926 --> 00:14:42,010
to wipe your, uh…
tushie, after going to the bathroom,

368
00:14:42,094 --> 00:14:44,388
and you said you were
listening to it, because at work,

369
00:14:44,472 --> 00:14:46,181
you're trying to teach
a computer to sing.

370
00:14:46,265 --> 00:14:49,643
And what was the punch line?

371
00:14:49,727 --> 00:14:51,979
Now I'm wondering,
does my father not know

372
00:14:52,063 --> 00:14:53,981
-how to go to the bathroom?
-Okay.

373
00:14:54,065 --> 00:14:55,983
-And if that's true, who taught me?
-I get it.

374
00:14:56,067 --> 00:14:57,398
Because my mother
never goes to the bathroom.

375
00:14:57,482 --> 00:14:57,943
That's enough.

376
00:14:58,027 --> 00:14:59,737
-I heard my name!
-No, you didn't.

377
00:14:59,821 --> 00:15:02,030
What else did you say? About Bell Labs?

378
00:15:02,114 --> 00:15:04,616
-About the work there?
-Nothing.

379
00:15:04,700 --> 00:15:06,869
No specifics about what I do?

380
00:15:06,953 --> 00:15:09,289
I don't know what you do.
I've never known what you do.

381
00:15:09,373 --> 00:15:11,833
Most of the time, I have no
idea what you're talking about.

382
00:15:11,917 --> 00:15:14,294
I have no idea why we're
having this conversation right now.

383
00:15:14,378 --> 00:15:16,296
All right.

384
00:15:16,380 --> 00:15:18,382
I believe you.

385
00:15:25,305 --> 00:15:27,599
We haven't finished our
Benjamin conversation yet.

386
00:15:27,683 --> 00:15:29,350
-Yes, we have.
-I want an answer.

387
00:15:29,434 --> 00:15:31,812
-Okay. No.
-You're right. Take your time.

388
00:15:34,147 --> 00:15:36,441
-What do you think?
-I think it's a piece of shit.

389
00:15:36,525 --> 00:15:39,152
That's the eighth chair
you said was a piece of shit.

390
00:15:39,236 --> 00:15:41,696
I believe all eight are
genuinely a piece of shit.

391
00:15:41,780 --> 00:15:44,449
Jackie, we can't throw
out every fucking chair.

392
00:15:44,533 --> 00:15:46,868
Now, just tell me, what can
you fix and what can't you fix?

393
00:15:46,952 --> 00:15:48,620
-Fix?
-Repair.

394
00:15:48,704 --> 00:15:50,497
-Me?
-Yeah, you.

395
00:15:50,581 --> 00:15:52,207
Who told you I can fix anything?

396
00:15:52,291 --> 00:15:53,875
I thought you were a carpenter.

397
00:15:53,959 --> 00:15:55,586
Who the fuck told you that?

398
00:15:55,670 --> 00:15:57,755
Isn't that what you did
before you worked here?

399
00:15:57,839 --> 00:16:00,424
No! Oh, wait.

400
00:16:00,508 --> 00:16:03,260
Yes, I did. I am a carpenter.

401
00:16:03,344 --> 00:16:05,596
So can you fix these?

402
00:16:05,680 --> 00:16:07,389
Absolutely.

403
00:16:07,473 --> 00:16:09,141
[PHONE RINGING]

404
00:16:09,225 --> 00:16:10,851
What?

405
00:16:10,935 --> 00:16:13,980
I just… Never mind.

406
00:16:17,317 --> 00:16:18,734
Gaslight.

407
00:16:18,818 --> 00:16:20,486
-WOMAN: <i>Susie Myerson?</i>
-Yeah?

408
00:16:20,570 --> 00:16:22,363
I'm calling on behalf of Sophie Lennon.

409
00:16:22,447 --> 00:16:24,365
-Oh, shit.
<i>-Excuse me?</i>

410
00:16:24,449 --> 00:16:28,244
I, um… I'm bleeding.
Uh, could I call you back?

411
00:16:28,328 --> 00:16:29,829
Miss Lennon requests your presence

412
00:16:29,913 --> 00:16:32,039
at her house this
Friday, one o'clock sharp.

413
00:16:32,123 --> 00:16:33,499
-What? Why?
<i>-She is requesting it.</i>

414
00:16:33,583 --> 00:16:35,167
<i>Friday, o'clock sharp.</i>

415
00:16:35,251 --> 00:16:36,919
Uh, Friday's not really good for me.

416
00:16:37,003 --> 00:16:38,879
My mistake.
She is demanding your presence

417
00:16:38,963 --> 00:16:40,881
at her house Friday, 1:00 sharp.

418
00:16:40,965 --> 00:16:42,759
<i>-But…</i>
-215 East 98th Street.

419
00:16:42,843 --> 00:16:44,970
Eat before you come.
Lunch will not be served.

420
00:16:45,054 --> 00:16:46,346
-Wait!
-[LINE CLICKS]

421
00:16:46,430 --> 00:16:48,306
-[SIGHS]
-[DIAL TONE]

422
00:16:48,390 --> 00:16:50,183
[UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]

423
00:16:50,267 --> 00:16:52,227
That was Sophie Lennon
summoning me to her house.

424
00:16:52,311 --> 00:16:54,396
Can you believe that?
After what Harry Drake did?

425
00:16:54,480 --> 00:16:56,565
After what she did to Midge?
Is she crazy?

426
00:16:56,649 --> 00:16:58,775
-You got to go.
-What do you mean, I got to go?

427
00:16:58,859 --> 00:17:00,569
-No way.
-You fucked up.

428
00:17:00,653 --> 00:17:02,696
You went off, you made things worse.

429
00:17:02,780 --> 00:17:06,825
Now you got to go eat some
shit to make things right for Midge.

430
00:17:06,909 --> 00:17:08,076
Midge wouldn't want me to eat shit.

431
00:17:08,160 --> 00:17:09,786
Doesn't matter what she wants.

432
00:17:09,870 --> 00:17:12,664
You're the manager.
You go to do what's best for your client.

433
00:17:12,748 --> 00:17:14,833
I don't like this side of you, Jackie.

434
00:17:14,917 --> 00:17:17,210
-What side?
-Rational. It's freaking me out.

435
00:17:17,294 --> 00:17:21,339
Look, one thing I know about,
even more than carpentry,

436
00:17:21,423 --> 00:17:24,175
and this is from personal experience

437
00:17:24,259 --> 00:17:27,554
in life, sometimes you got
to eat a whole lot of shit.

438
00:17:27,638 --> 00:17:31,017
Piles of it.
More shit than you can imagine.

439
00:17:31,101 --> 00:17:34,145
If you took a pack of
wolves with stomach issues,

440
00:17:34,229 --> 00:17:36,272
and locked them in your
apartment for a month,

441
00:17:36,356 --> 00:17:38,190
and then came home with a spoon,

442
00:17:38,274 --> 00:17:40,610
that's the amount of
shit I'm talking about.

443
00:17:40,694 --> 00:17:42,194
Thank you for the vivid imagery.

444
00:17:42,278 --> 00:17:44,572
Life is basically an
all-you-can-eat shit show.

445
00:17:44,656 --> 00:17:47,158
-You're disgusting.
-Yup, but I'm right.

446
00:17:50,078 --> 00:17:53,289
Hey, I fixed it.
How the fuck do you like that?

447
00:17:53,373 --> 00:17:55,375
[JACKIE CHUCKLES]

448
00:17:57,293 --> 00:18:00,087
Joel? It's me. Can I come in?

449
00:18:00,171 --> 00:18:02,006
[ESTHER BABBLES]

450
00:18:02,090 --> 00:18:04,091
[ESTHER SHOUTS]

451
00:18:04,175 --> 00:18:05,885
Hi. Sorry I'm late.

452
00:18:05,969 --> 00:18:07,261
Ethan, grab your bag.

453
00:18:07,345 --> 00:18:09,013
-Your mother's here.
-Everything okay?

454
00:18:09,097 --> 00:18:10,431
You were supposed to be here at 6:00.

455
00:18:10,515 --> 00:18:11,974
I know. I'm sorry.

456
00:18:12,058 --> 00:18:13,643
They are both fed, but Ethan's decided

457
00:18:13,727 --> 00:18:15,771
he wants an additional
bedtime meal, so you figure out

458
00:18:15,855 --> 00:18:18,231
what the hell that means so
I can be prepared next time.

459
00:18:18,315 --> 00:18:19,775
-Joel…
-Bye, pal.

460
00:18:19,859 --> 00:18:21,818
-See you in a few days.
-Joel, what's the matter?

461
00:18:21,902 --> 00:18:23,570
-Nothing.
-Why are you giving me the brush-off?

462
00:18:23,654 --> 00:18:25,238
I'm not giving you the brush-off.

463
00:18:25,322 --> 00:18:27,366
I have to work, you have to go.
Case closed.

464
00:18:27,450 --> 00:18:29,284
Okay, but…

465
00:18:29,368 --> 00:18:31,954
Okay, I'll drop them off on Friday.

466
00:18:32,038 --> 00:18:34,040
-Yup.
-Come on.

467
00:18:35,833 --> 00:18:38,877
I heard about Ethan meeting
your new friend at the park.

468
00:18:38,961 --> 00:18:42,506
-Oh, Joel…
-You know, I have friends, too.

469
00:18:42,590 --> 00:18:45,092
Maybe I should introduce
them to the kids at the park.

470
00:18:45,176 --> 00:18:47,010
I'm sorry. It was a mistake.

471
00:18:47,094 --> 00:18:49,096
Mama told him we were there.
I didn't invite him.

472
00:18:49,180 --> 00:18:50,555
Those are my children, Midge.

473
00:18:50,639 --> 00:18:52,265
I have a right to know
who's meeting them.

474
00:18:52,349 --> 00:18:54,142
-I agree. I told him that.
-Oh, you did? When?

475
00:18:54,226 --> 00:18:56,561
When he showed up.
I told him that you didn't know about it,

476
00:18:56,645 --> 00:18:58,438
and I needed to tell you
before I introduced them.

477
00:18:58,522 --> 00:18:59,856
This is bullshit.

478
00:18:59,940 --> 00:19:02,193
-I thought we were playing nice.
-We are.

479
00:19:02,277 --> 00:19:03,903
My kids!

480
00:19:03,987 --> 00:19:05,780
Mine! I should be informed

481
00:19:05,864 --> 00:19:07,699
before you hand them over to another man.

482
00:19:07,783 --> 00:19:09,951
I didn't hand them over to another man.

483
00:19:10,035 --> 00:19:12,286
He showed up by accident.
It was not intentional.

484
00:19:12,370 --> 00:19:14,205
Don't make this a thing.

485
00:19:14,289 --> 00:19:16,583
It is a thing! It's a big fu…

486
00:19:18,043 --> 00:19:20,086
I have to work. You have to go.

487
00:19:20,170 --> 00:19:21,546
You're being unreasonable.

488
00:19:21,630 --> 00:19:23,631
Oh, am I? Well, you should leave me then.

489
00:19:23,715 --> 00:19:25,049
Oh, wait.

490
00:19:25,133 --> 00:19:27,218
I didn't leave you. You left me!

491
00:19:27,302 --> 00:19:29,637
And then you left me back!
